@Module – class that provides dependencies.
@Provides – method inside @Module that returns the dependency instance.
@Inject – requests a dependency injection (used on constructor, field, or method).
@Component – bridge between @Module and @Inject.
@Singleton – ensures only one instance of the dependency is created.
@Scope – defines a custom lifecycle scope.
@Qualifier – allows multiple instances of the same type.
@Binds – binds an interface to its implementation in an abstract module.

@Test – marks a method as a test case.
@Before – runs before each test (setup).
@BeforeClass – runs once before all tests in the class.
@After – runs after each test (teardown).
@AfterClass – runs once after all tests.
@Ignore – skips the test.
@Test(timeout=500) – fails the test if it exceeds the specified time.

SupervisorScope is a coroutine builder that creates a new child scope and acts as a supervisor for coroutines launched within it.

Unlike a regular coroutine scope, if a child coroutine fails with an exception, the SupervisorScope does not cancel the remaining child coroutines. Each child is independent.

Example:
suspend fun myCoroutine() {
    supervisorScope {
        launch {
            // do some work
        }
        launch {
            // do some other work — runs even if the first launch fails
        }
    }
}

By default, all classes and functions in Kotlin are final, meaning they cannot be inherited or overridden. To allow inheritance or overriding, you must explicitly mark the class or function with the open keyword.

Example:
open class Animal {
    open fun speak() { }
}

class Dog : Animal() {
    override fun speak() { }
}

A higher-order function is a function that either takes another function as a parameter, returns a function, or both.

Example:
fun passMeFunction(abc: () -> Unit) {
    // executes the passed function
    abc()
}

Higher-order functions are the foundation for features like scope functions (let, apply, run), collection operations (map, filter), and coroutine builders (launch, async).

Primary Constructor:
Defined in the class header. It cannot contain any code directly; initialization logic goes in an init{} block.
Example: class Person(val name: String, val age: Int)

Secondary Constructor:
Defined inside the class body using the constructor keyword. You must explicitly call the primary constructor from a secondary constructor using this().

Example:
class Person(val name: String) {
    constructor(name: String, age: Int) : this(name) {
        // additional setup
    }
}

In Kotlin, a Singleton is created using the object keyword. The Kotlin compiler ensures only one instance is ever created.

Example:
object DatabaseManager {
    fun getConnection() { }
}

This is equivalent to Java's double-checked locking Singleton pattern but is much simpler and thread-safe by default.

Kotlin does not have a static keyword like Java. Instead, we use a companion object to define members that belong to the class itself rather than to any instance. A companion object allows you to call methods or access properties without creating an object of the class.

Example:
class Mentor {
    companion object {
        fun guide() {
            println("Guiding...")
        }
    }
}

// Call without creating an instance:
Mentor.guide()

This is the Kotlin equivalent of Java's static methods and static fields.

crossinline is used in inline functions to prevent non-local returns from a lambda parameter.

By default, a lambda passed to an inline function can use return to exit the outer calling function (non-local return). crossinline disallows this, ensuring the lambda can only return from itself.

Example:
inline fun execute(crossinline action: () -> Unit) {
    val runnable = Runnable { action() }
    runnable.run()
}

Use crossinline when the lambda will be executed in a different execution context, such as inside a Runnable or a callback, where a non-local return would be unsafe or ambiguous.
